            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sonali Kaur Miller\u2019s identity is a testament to California\u2019s layered histories. The daughter of a Yurok tribe member from the North Coast and a Punjabi Sikh immigrant mother, Sonali grew up in the Central Valley, navigating a childhood woven from two distinct, yet parallel, narratives of resilience. Her name itself is a bridge: \"Sonali Kaur\" from her mother, honoring tradition and the concept of *seva* (selfless service), and \"Miller\" from her father, grounding her in the ancestral lands of her tribe. Weekends were spent either at a powwow, feeling the drum's pulse, or at the local gurdwara, absorbing the peaceful hymns. This dual upbringing instilled in her a profound understanding of marginalized communities and the systemic barriers they face.\n\nThis awareness became her professional compass. At UC Berkeley, she saw firsthand how the tech boom was creating a new form of inequality. The digital divide wasn't an academic concept; it was the reality for her relatives on the reservation and the elderly members of her mother\u2019s Sikh community struggling with online services. This inspired her to pursue a Master's in Public Policy at USC, focusing specifically on how technology could be wielded for public good, not just private profit.\n\nNow, as a Digital Services Strategist for the City and County of San Francisco, Sonali\u2019s life is the fruition of her goals. She lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Mission District, a neighborhood whose vibrant, chaotic energy reminds her of the confluence of cultures she loves. Her 3.8-mile commute on the MUNI J Church line is a daily ritual of observation, watching the city\u2019s diverse population move and interact. Her work involves streamlining access to city resources, designing user-friendly portals, and ensuring that non-English speakers and those with disabilities can navigate the city\u2019s digital infrastructure.\n\nHer personal life is a close-knit circle of friends from grad school and work who share her civic-minded passion. While her $145,000 income affords her a comfortable life, her joy comes from mission-driven work. Sonali\u2019s aspiration is to lead a statewide digital equity initiative, ensuring that the technological progress born in California serves all its people. For her, building a better app is about honoring her ancestors by forging a more just and accessible future."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was ten. One Saturday, the earth shook with the Grand Entry drum at a powwow near the Klamath. The next morning, the same deep pulse echoed in her chest from the harmonium during kirtan at the gurdwara. She realized then they were the same song\u2014a hymn of survival and community. It wasn\u2019t a divided self she felt, but a doubled strength. This memory became the blueprint for her life's work: finding the shared rhythm connecting disparate worlds and amplifying it for all to hear.\n\n2.\nIn her sophomore year at Berkeley, sitting in a cafe surrounded by students coding the next big startup, she took a call from her uncle. He was on the reservation, trying to apply for a grant but the website kept crashing on his slow connection. The injustice of it hit her like a physical blow: brilliance and capital flowed one way, while her own family was locked out. The digital divide was no longer a term in a textbook; it was a wall around her people. That day, her path crystallized.\n\n3.\nTwo years into her job with the city, she volunteered at a workshop in the Tenderloin. She spent an hour with an elderly Punjabi woman, gently guiding her hand on the mouse to sign up for city benefits. When they finished, the woman, who reminded Sonali of her grandmother, placed a hand on her head and said, \"Tusaan seva keeti\" (You have done service). In that moment, the abstract policy work became profoundly personal. It was her mother's teaching made real, a quiet fulfillment more valuable than any promotion.\n\n4.\nOne rainy Tuesday, the J Church stalled near Dolores Park. Trapped between a day-laborer asleep on his backpack and a tech worker scrolling on a glowing screen, Sonali looked out the fogged window at the city lights. This train car, with its mix of languages, ambitions, and exhaustion, was San Francisco in miniature. It was the public she served. A wave of profound affection for its chaotic, imperfect humanity washed over her. This wasn't just a commute; it was a daily renewal of her vows to the city.\n\n5.\nThe night her team launched a simplified digital portal for small business permits, she didn't celebrate with drinks. Instead, she walked to a quiet spot with a view of the Bay and thought of her father's stories of Yurok people managing the Klamath River\u2019s resources for generations. She wasn't building weirs or fishing rights, but she was creating access and ensuring fairness. In the cool night air, she felt an ancestral nod of approval. This, her work of building digital pathways, was simply a modern form of stewarding the community."
